BTW: only red backlight makes sense because of the wavelength. Blue for example is too high of a frequency...short wavelength...which means that the light will scatter too much at the edges of the symbols, numbers and letters on the keys...thus the letters appear too fuzzy.

Red light has a long wavelength = low frequency...and that leads to a razor sharp picture of the symbols, numbers and letters.

Oh hey, I've got that Arteck! Well, not THAT Arteck, but their much shorter bluetooth version. Actually quite good for less than $20, and the metal baseplate actually feels really nice on it.

Worth the note that they don't hold up super-well to longer use - first one ended up with a couple keys dying after a few months, second one is showing signs of some of the keys starting down the same route, though still usable - but, if you can get into contact with their customer support (I had to go searching to find an email that worked), they barely even bother to ask any questions besides "where can we send the replacement". Probably to be expected with this cheap of a board, I'm sure it'd cost them more to even attempt to repair one, and they'd rather just have your good review on Amazon and send you something new. Which, hey, works for me, I just wanted an inexpensive alternative to typing on a tablet screen. Second one has lasted longer than the first did as well.

Would I game on it? Probably not, mostly because of those keys wearing out pretty fast, though maybe the full-size one stands up to more abuse. But yeah I'd probably still buy and use another one after the one I have dies, it's pretty straightforward, low-profile, and comfortable to type on (for what it is).

LTT, please!
At least make a video about the various North-American keyboard layouts and TRY THEM ALL for yourselves. Let's make some sort of arrangement. Once you get used to some layouts which seem weird at first, you realize that some can be better. While others worse.
Examples:
Canada should instate this one everywhere. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSA_keyboard
Yes, narrow left-shift, but it's totally fine. Yes, tall and narrow Enter key, but you quickly get used to it and it's totally fine.
Now here are some that are really bad.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keyboard_layout#/media/File:Physical_keyboard_layouts_comparison_ANSI_ISO_KS_ABNT_JIS.png
101/104 ANSI (Dvorak keyboard layout) : I hate that one. Missing letters and accents, Enter key narrow vertically. That extra key between Enter and Backspace is hard to reach and if you miss, something very bad happens.
102/105 ISO : Extra keys! Not bad! But I want more of them.
104/107 ABNT : Yes, better! Moar!
101/104 variant : I think I hate this one the most. That tiny Backspace key is the worst. And the gigantic Enter key is just wasteful, we could have had more keys!
103/106 KS : Burn it with a lot of fire! I know I want more keys, but not a smaller Space bar. There are some things that you shouldn't cut off.
106/109 JIS : Never seen this one. It may be the worst ever.

I DARE you, double-dare you, to try out these various layouts. DO IT!

These recommendations are decent, but if you step your budget up an extra 10 - 15$, you can get yourself something that is really, really good and will last you a lot longer.
At the absolute lowest end, is the Motospeed CK61 or CK62. Both are decent BLUETOOTH keyboards, with a bright RGB, and mechanical keys. The only downside being that its only Bluetooth 3.0 with lag being pretty noticable. These cost around 35-43$.
On the medium budget, you can easily and happily go with the Dierya DK61 or Reddragon K91 or even the Koyal Kludge. These are very bang for the buck gaming keyboard with mechanical switches, true RGB, and also a solid build. These are around 50$
And on the highest but still budget area, you can get the
1. Dierya X Kemove DK61 PRO which is actually much better than the DK61, featuring awesome RGB, mechanical switches, good quality keycaps and also Bluetooth 5.1! Gaming can be done on this and its really good.
2. Kemove K2/K6 really good keyboards with poor RGB, and personally i just don‚Äôt like the feel of them.

Why would somebody buy wireless keyboard? Here, I'll recap what people have been saying + my own experience:
- If you're using multiple computers, (desktop and laptop and/or tablets), switching input with a flick of a switch is very convenient.
- If you're mobile, you don't need the extra baggage that is the physical cable itself.
- Related to previous point, connecting/disconnecting cables introduce wear and tear.
- Easier to clean. Especially if you're in a dusty environment where any presence of cable can attract dust real quick.
- If you're a gamer, most games don't even need low latency input. Even then, just like what the video shows, good budget wireless keyboards' latency is not even that bad.

Apple can go burn in hell for their business practice for all I care, but blindly hating something without trying to see the other side's point of view makes you a moron too ‚ù§Ô∏è

i tend to switch every other day between my Logitech G710+ and Lenovo Trackpint Keyboard II wireless.
Bought the Lenovo for work, coz of the nipple... yup, i'm one of those thinkpad guys.

but actually the Lenovo wireless stands very well. The trackpoint mouse feels like it has less lag than my Logitech G700s in wireless mode. i indeed do note use the wireless mode of this mouse because one can feel the lag even while web browsing.

But this wireless laptop stlye keyboard is very very nice to type on, and in shootes i like the short key travel for twich reactions.
only con: it's rather pricey for just an essential keyboard. Can be used with 2.4 GHz dongle, BT 5.0 and USB cable, quick switch between dongle and BT with slider button, and an extra slider for power on off. One charge lasts for a month on 12h every day use.
After 30 seconds it goes to sleep mode. Waking up takes about 200-250 ms (by feel) and does not swallow any input. 6 key roll over. which is plenty enough for gamer use ;-)

Fn key toggle with indicator, Windows and android mode (slider switch).
Its great for travel, couch, on lap use. light and compact.

But there is one (for some maybe two) potential deal breaker. The FN and ctrl keys are switched. For those who are not familiar with thinkpad keyboards this might be very very hard to get used to.
The dicision was here, that the ctrl IS next to the Super/Windows key. period. But many have the muscle memory to just come from the keyboards edge to the first key, which is usually the ctrl key.
So, if you are Type A: Ctrl is left of the windows key, there will be no issue. If you are Type B who reach for the edge of the keyboard and find the ctrl, you will really really have to grow a custom on this keyboard.
Second neclegible downer might the trackpoint. some do not use it, but are still annoyed even when they pull the rubber nipple off.

If one wants to disable the trackpoint and mouse buttons under the spacebar for good: pull the nipple and disable the hardware device, in device manager.
The Keyboard identifieys itself as 2 seperate devices, thus the mouse can be disabled by disabling the driver.

- USB-C and Thunderbolt hubs/docking stations;
- Chargers - USB-C PD, USB 3.0, Lightning, single and multi port, with and without digital displays, GaN, etc;
- Portable displays - with or without battery, touchscreen or not, etc;
- Portable keyboard and mouse solutions - foldable, RF and bluetooth based, multi function, trackballs, ergonomic mice, etc;
- External batteries - multi port, PD, 100W for laptops and multiple devices at the same time, fast charging compatibility, etc;
- Portable projectors - laser, led, bulb based, with without OS, ports, etc;
- Portable routers/access point/HDDs/"companion" devices - seems this category fell out of fashion these days, but you know;
- Other portable accessories. Printers, scanners, speakers, etc.
- Perhaps some production stuff? Microphones in several categories, audio recorders, mixers, live switchers, webcams and cameras for a specific category such as live streaming, etc;

@Mizz141 Yeah, all the tall-enter US keyboards I have seen relocate the backslash key to replace half the enter key. I'm sure there are some that place it elsewhere but I don't recall ever seeing one. I would be more accepting of the style if they didn't shrink the backspace, which is just inexcusable for ergonomics and efficiency. Other country layouts, where the local ISO variant is the standard and there aren't any big ergonomic violations like a tiny backspace key, it surely makes perfect sense for natives to those places to prefer their local standard layout. I'm just speaking from experience with US keyboards (and ranting about my gripe with tiny backspace keys). I don't know why the backslash is wider on ANSI keyboards but I do use backslashes pretty commonly as a programmer. Ideally, I'd have designed it to use that space for an m-dash (‚Äî) or degree symbol (¬∞). But personally, I still don't see what value is provided by a double-height ever key if it's still a longer reach to hit the extended upper part of the key‚Äî and that extra height could be used for something else, plus it breaks visual consistency with all other keys being one unit tall, and it might introduce mechanical complexity and therefore extra cost for a special mechanism that works with a taller key. In other countries, I'm certain the ISO layout makes sense but for US keyboards, the standard ANSI layout is way better. (And I'm sorry if I'm confusing certain aspects or nuances of the ANSI/ISO specs as they relate to US keyboards, since I am generalizing them to basically a difference in the enter/backslash/backspace configuration which is the only difference I have noticed in the wild).

@SpookzNGlory
>not many countries

Its like... the whole EU and more?

@Keavon Chambers Holy shit the US makes the Backspace smaller? That's not ISO Standart then. ISO says that the Backspace must be 2U and the Enter key is also a special size.

I use CH ISO and the Bigger Enter key gives more space for other keys that wouldn't fit on an ANSI layout, also why the fuck is a \ so huge on ANSI? totally pointless.

The extra height to an ISO enter key is useless because it's further to reach up and right, when the key is easily reachable with the pinky to the immediate right of the apostrophe, requiring the least finger movement or strain. The taller enter key then displaces the backslash key, and frequently it does this by splitting the backspace key in half and repurposing the left half for the new backslash key. What is left is an absolutely tiny, hard-to-reach, strain-inducing backspace key. And backspace is one of the very most popular keys on the keyboard, probably even more common than the enter key in many tasks. So in exchange for a taller enter key which provides zero benefit, you get a tiny and hard to reach backspace key. There is literally no upside. However I am speaking about US keyboards with the taller enter key‚Äî I can't comment on other countries' layouts because their placement of backslash, backspace, and many other keys are wildly different.

This year I got second Logitech K350. First one I had 9 years and now it is used on my parents pc - still going on, but keys just don't work so smooth like in a new one. Since I do a lot of work and gaming on my PC, I can assure you that even after 9 years those "stickers" on keys won't peel off ;). One thing I should mention - they DON'T work good near or in a USB 3.0 port - due to the nano reciver being interupted by USB 3.0 interference when you have a USB 3.0 device running eg. pendrive, but you just need a USB 2.0 extension cable (I have 1 m), that you can plug in USB 3.0 port in your PC, and my reciver is pluged into that extension cable and it works. BUT if u have a laptop and have two usb 3.0 ports near or you have usb 2.0 and usb 3.0 port near, then your keyboard will lag when you use other port eg. when I plugged nano reciver to USB 2.0 and there was a USB 3.0 port near that I used to plug a pendrive, my keyboard started to lag when I was transfering files, but, as soon as I plugged the nano reciver on the other side in a USB 3.0 port - it worked normally. Read Logitech forums, and you will know whats going on. Don't know if they improved nano reciver to work with USB 3.0. PS. You can plug up to X devices to it so if u buy a mouse, you can use one reciver instead of two but also remeber that gaming mouses won't pair with standard nano reciver and you have to use dedicated to your gaming mouse (I have G700 also 10 years now ;) ).

* a NUMPAD (why is it even a thing that many keyboards don't have numpads anymore??)
* illuminated (I type in the dark a lot, I don't care about RGB)

Now the keyboard itself works great. I like the more silent and flatter keys and never saw any noticable input delay. I don't play FPS so maaaaybe it is noticable there, but in any other genre the wire is nothing but a nuisance for zero benefits.

I really need a better alternative .. preferably one where keys are NOT mounted with tiny little plastic latches - not just so they don't break by themselves after a few years, but also so I can remove them without a 50% chance of something breaking to clean the keyboard .. @RainbowSushii From your home there will be a copper connection to your nearest Fiber entry point, there the signal will be converted into a Fiber signal and sent through to the other end, where it will be re-encoded to a Copper signal.

With an FTTH Connection (Fiber To The Home) the only latency is your Ethernet cabling, router and PC.
I eliminated that and went with Fiber everywhere, even into my PC.

Effectively only giving me the latency at the other end of the Fiber, which are the game servers.

And, it largely works fine for gaming (can't speak for ultra-fast shooters running in the 4 digit FPS for competition gamers, as I don't generally enjoy those.)

No kinda brag, just feedback in case anyone is looking to pick something like that up. I use a TV for large-screen relaxing gaming, and a monitor for at desk work/gaming that are perpendicular, so having a keyboard/mouse that I can turn with me when changing which screen I am using as a gaming screen is fantastic, and in over a year of ownership, dropped input from either has been sub-two digit occurrences. OK, so latency is acceptable, but what number of keys can you press at the same time? My current daily driver is a wired keyboard that support N-key rollover. That means it can detect all the keys on the board as they are pressed even if it happens at the same time. While that might be seen as being overkill it surely beats some cheap keyboards that support detecting only a few key presses at the same time. Actually the basic USB keyboard support only stretches to six keys being pressed concurrently. It took several years before someone solved that. I've never bothered to learn exactly how they did solve it, but most gaming keyboards on the market now either support N-key rollover or at least a high enough number of concurrent key presses that it doesn't really matter.

"But hey, six key presses at the same time is more than enough!" someone will say. Well it just might, but then in some games it might not. I remember when I got whacked over the head by the key rollover limit of a cheap keyboard. It was way back and the game was the original release of Earthworm Jim for the PC. I worked my way through the game slowly as I really wasn't very good at platform games. And then I ran into a wall. There was this certain level that I simply couldn't get past. It wasn't that I didn't know how to do it, or that I got the timing wrong, no it was just that the move I had to do became impossible as my keyboard couldn't register enough simultaneous key presses. No matter what I tried I couldn't perform the move I had to do, and for a long time I thought it was my fault. Eventually I figured out that the same move, just doing it while moving to the left instead of the right worked very well as given the keyboards construction all of the keys needed for that would work. But trying to do the same combo move but moving left was impossible with my keyboard.

Also traditionally membrane keyboards has had very strange rollover limitations. My old cheap keyboard was one of these, and depending on what keys you pressed it would lock out some others from detection. That was what bit me when playing Earthworm Jim.
I'm not sure how modern membrane keyboards handle this, but I do know that it's very uncommon that they support N-key rollover. Actually I don't know of any that do...

So what level of key rollover does these wireless keyboards support? Is it the default USB limit of 6 or is it more or less than that?

Food for thought.
19ms wired
cheap 39 ms
cheap 46ms
cheap 44 ms
cheap 51 ms
Average=45ms or 137% higher latency
OR 9.36x the difference between 240hz and 144hz and 3.5x the difference between 60hz and 144hz
Infact the difference in added latency between the wired and those keyboards in terms of framerate is equal to going from 60fps down to 23fps, OR if you really wanna scare yourself those extra 26ms of added latency is equal to going from 240hz (4.16ms per frame) down to 33fps. Which is why esports people who go for 240hz screens want everything else to be as respensive.

The other 2 logitechs ~21ms however while about 10.5% higher latency for the average gamer the extra 2ms wont matter nearly as much.

I had the Logitech K350 for around four months. It was terrible. Keys started to get mushy after 1 week of gaming and I don't press the keys that hard. The feet easily scratch wooden surfaces and don't have that well of a grip to them. After one month, I started noticing that keys would automatically actuate themselves without any contact and some just wouldn't work. The "a" key in particular. The media keys aren't that great and after two weeks of usage the volume up and down buttons started sliding on the axis they were on. I did recently take apart the keyboard because it was broken and I had nothing better to do, and it seemed like the keycaps were easily scratched by the key cap puller included (hidden under the space bar). It has barely any deck flex though, and in the little time that this keyboard functioned, it did its job.
